```cpp
void process_activity( Character &dummy, bool pass_time )
{
    do {
        dummy.mod_moves( dummy.get_speed() );
        while( dummy.get_moves() > 0 && dummy.activity ) {
            dummy.activity.do_turn( dummy );
        }
    } while( dummy.activity );
}
```

The outer loop continues as long as `dummy.activity` is not null. When the activity nulls itself in `do_turn`, the inner loop terminates (since `dummy.activity` is now false). Then the outer loop checks `while( dummy.activity )` — false, so it exits.

But what if the activity doesn't null itself in the first call? Let me check: maybe `stage_think` takes multiple turns to process (because of the route probe cost at line 13614: `you.mod_moves( -1 )`).

